WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:07.920
Hi, it's wonderful to see you here. It's been a great conference with lots of deep and technical conversations

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:14.320
But my presentation isn't technical. I just want you to have some fun and hear my story

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:22.440
Every story got a lesson and mine isn't different. It has a few and I hope you enjoy them and find them useful

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:25.799
Imagine this

00:00:25.799 --> 00:00:31.480
You are a team of professional swimmers. You've been swimming in the swimming pool for years for 20 years

00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:37.439
The temperature has been comfortable. The water is calm. Each swimmer has their own lane

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:40.840
it's warm bright and cozy and

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:46.119
One day you are told that the pool will be closing forever

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:53.880
You will have to learn how to swim in the open waters in the ocean that you've never seen before let alone swamming

00:00:55.880 --> 00:00:57.880
Your imagination goes wild

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:00.560
strong winds

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:02.400
rough shores, scary creatures

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:07.519
It's how we felt in my organization when we started that migration

00:01:07.639 --> 00:01:14.080
When we decided to move from proprietary toolkit to open source R and Python

00:01:14.639 --> 00:01:16.680
My name is Katerina Gapanenko

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:21.519
I work at the Canadian Institute for Health Information a national organization

00:01:21.519 --> 00:01:25.919
That's for 30 years collects analyzes and reports health information

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:29.120
There I led a project of this massive

00:01:29.879 --> 00:01:33.239
transformation from proprietary toolkit to open source

00:01:34.480 --> 00:01:41.400
we have over 350 analysts and we have tons of code and over 500 products and

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:49.919
Some of the code has been developed 20 years ago by people who are not longer with the organization and we treat this code as

00:01:50.839 --> 00:01:55.680
Vintage wine. Today, I would like to share the story of our transformation

00:01:55.879 --> 00:02:00.800
It was a multi-year massive project with a lot of stories to tell

00:02:01.239 --> 00:02:04.639
One presentation ago you heard Yvonne Kina's story

00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:10.119
She was talking about the ripples of change her story was about the same project as mine

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:14.080
But I'd like to share my perspective as the business owner

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:18.360
I will tell you everything from the beginning to the end from top to bottom and

00:02:18.839 --> 00:02:25.479
If you're considering a similar transformation in your organization, you may find both stories useful

00:02:26.279 --> 00:02:33.160
So three years ago, we stood at the edge of a cliff the water looked powerful, but intimidating

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:40.160
We couldn't just test the waters. We needed to jump so we did but why we jumped

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:42.199
first

00:02:42.199 --> 00:02:47.000
Sustainability proprietary toolkit has been our safe pool for years

00:02:47.479 --> 00:02:49.479
Stable vendor-supported

00:02:49.600 --> 00:02:51.600
but inflexible and

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.399
Expensive and it was hard to integrate into existing

00:02:56.039 --> 00:02:59.839
Workflows and we were modernizing our workflows as well

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:07.300
Second the talent more and more analysts coming to the organization with existing R and Python knowledge

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:10.960
They were frustrated with our outdated tools

00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:19.399
Our existing staff were curious about what's going on outside of these proprietary tools in the open waters

00:03:20.679 --> 00:03:22.360
Innovation and collaboration

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:28.639
We couldn't just keep up with the speed of a modern data science if we stayed in this closed ecosystem

00:03:28.839 --> 00:03:34.919
We felt that we were missing the boat in this one. And that is why we decided to go from

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:36.759
closed

00:03:36.759 --> 00:03:39.759
tools from proprietary tools to open source

00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:45.279
Very quickly way and discovered three things that could pull us under

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.559
Technical hurdles we needed to build new environment new ideas

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.759
Parallel computing get we needed to learn all about all these tools

00:03:56.759 --> 00:04:01.679
And we felt at that time that we see just a tip of the iceberg

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:05.160
Then the next one is cultural resistance

00:04:06.039 --> 00:04:13.279
Learning in general is emotional like waves. It comes with excitement frustration anxiety and joy

00:04:14.279 --> 00:04:18.160
Learning major skills at work is even more difficult

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:24.359
As an organization we understood that this change will not be smooth

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:28.880
The workload we had a lot of product to deliver

00:04:29.079 --> 00:04:33.940
We had too little time to learn and we had no time to migrate the code

00:04:34.339 --> 00:04:36.339
The constant pressure

00:04:36.540 --> 00:04:41.299
Circled beneath us as sharks if we didn't address it, it could have been fatal

00:04:42.299 --> 00:04:45.059
To help us overcome all these three dangers

00:04:45.179 --> 00:04:51.459
We built three aids at three different levels at the organizational level. We built executive support

00:04:52.179 --> 00:04:58.140
At the project level. We built a diverse project leading team a small team and

00:04:58.420 --> 00:05:03.839
At the individual level at the analyst level we built mentorship and training programs

00:05:04.299 --> 00:05:09.700
These three aids help us to survive and succeed without them. We might have sunk

00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:18.579
Executive support I see the executive support as a lighthouse as the beacon guiding everyone through the rough waters

00:05:19.299 --> 00:05:22.179
Steady and visible and given directions

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:30.059
We started gradually at the beginning. We plan to migrate 50% of our code in several years

00:05:30.339 --> 00:05:34.739
But it was very challenging to figure out how to split the organization in two

00:05:35.140 --> 00:05:39.100
How do we go about it? Is it gonna be right hand and left leg?

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:45.619
Is it gonna be ways up and ways down how to decide who will stay in the closed?

00:05:45.779 --> 00:05:51.779
Environment and who will go and try the open open waters open source at the same time

00:05:51.779 --> 00:05:57.179
we started talking to a lot of external organizations who started the same transition as ours and

00:05:57.779 --> 00:06:03.980
All of them who maintain and maintain two systems at the same time told us that it was very challenging

00:06:04.739 --> 00:06:07.420
Because you and they needed to maintain two servers

00:06:07.700 --> 00:06:15.220
They needed to maintain two groups of analysts and it was difficult to collaborate among analysts and share their code

00:06:15.739 --> 00:06:23.260
so we came back to our analysts and to our executive team and we explained to them all these challenges and

00:06:23.940 --> 00:06:28.420
With their support we decided to make one bold call

00:06:29.420 --> 00:06:35.660
single hard deadline every script every data set and every analyst

00:06:36.820 --> 00:06:41.339
Our executive gave us space and cleared our workload

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:45.980
They made learning a priority for everyone in the organization

00:06:46.420 --> 00:06:50.380
They showed their support and they were a part of our celebrations

00:06:50.940 --> 00:06:55.660
We created a few KPIs to tell about the progress in training

00:06:56.420 --> 00:06:58.859
immigration and in the environment adoption

00:06:59.380 --> 00:07:03.619
Our second success factor was the project leading team itself

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:09.140
Think about it as a rescue team with diverse strengths and skills and tools

00:07:09.779 --> 00:07:14.700
small versatile and ready for our waters and designed to save lives

00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:20.779
We had different strengths and different skills some of us new hi-hi business

00:07:21.220 --> 00:07:24.820
Others new hi-hi products very well and the legacy code

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:29.940
Others new are in Python, but some of us were not technical at all

00:07:30.420 --> 00:07:36.859
But they were able to read the room and manage emotions and they were able to organize all

00:07:37.100 --> 00:07:39.820
Sorts of events that we had throughout the projects

00:07:40.339 --> 00:07:44.220
Others were great with project management and reporting

00:07:44.940 --> 00:07:51.739
We were just a handful of people with different strengths, but we were bound by the same mission

00:07:52.339 --> 00:07:58.619
But despite of our diversity we operated as one crew. We did everything together

00:07:59.380 --> 00:08:01.380
brainstorming making decision

00:08:01.619 --> 00:08:05.899
Executing and we did it fast because we trusted each other

00:08:06.779 --> 00:08:09.100
And we build trust around us

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:14.579
We instilled trust in analysts that they could learn and they could deliver

00:08:14.980 --> 00:08:22.619
We build trust with executives that our project team could deliver. We showed everyone that the project would succeed

00:08:23.380 --> 00:08:26.220
That mean being honest about challenging

00:08:26.619 --> 00:08:34.979
Listening to everyone's worries trying to unpack those of worries and get to the bottom of their concerns and show empathy

00:08:35.380 --> 00:08:42.500
All this communication took time and patience in many cases we needed to adjust people as expectations

00:08:43.020 --> 00:08:48.260
And tell them in advance what's happening in some case in case

00:08:48.780 --> 00:08:52.780
Adjusting expectations wasn't easy. I will give just one example

00:08:53.419 --> 00:09:00.619
At the very beginning our analyst felt that the new environment should be as stable as the old environment

00:09:00.780 --> 00:09:08.380
So in in in other words, they didn't expect the ocean water to be salty with seagrass and jellyfish

00:09:09.539 --> 00:09:17.299
So we had to explain to them in several different ways and several at several different occasions. That is not the case

00:09:18.020 --> 00:09:22.179
But through this communication, we also understood their worries

00:09:22.179 --> 00:09:29.460
We understood what was the barrier for them and why stable communication stable environment was important for them

00:09:29.619 --> 00:09:34.419
So eventually we were we were adjusting their expectations, but we also

00:09:35.619 --> 00:09:41.219
Change our view on what they were worried about so we found the middle ground

00:09:41.900 --> 00:09:46.460
The whole transformation wasn't just technical. It's also

00:09:47.340 --> 00:09:50.020
Emotional and it's the emotional in the first place

00:09:51.380 --> 00:09:56.940
Understanding acknowledging addressing people's worries is at most important

00:09:57.940 --> 00:10:03.820
Then the training when we realized how much code we need to migrate

00:10:04.299 --> 00:10:11.580
We started looking elsewhere to understand how we can deliver the project within the time frame that we set

00:10:12.179 --> 00:10:18.659
We explored hiring external gurus or hiring an army of co-op students

00:10:19.219 --> 00:10:24.099
Outsourcing the whole thing outside of our organization or using automation

00:10:24.700 --> 00:10:31.419
We waited all these options and decided to invest in our analyst in the people we already had

00:10:32.020 --> 00:10:37.739
We wanted to equip our analyst with the tools and skills and support they needed

00:10:39.700 --> 00:10:46.700
We knew analysts couldn't just jump in the waters and start swimming so we built a learning

00:10:47.099 --> 00:10:48.380
ecosystem for them

00:10:48.380 --> 00:10:56.020
We created variety of options for everyone to choose from it was self-paced or in class short long

00:10:56.739 --> 00:11:01.900
Created inside the house or off-the-shelf courses at the beginning

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:06.340
They benefited the most from our courses that we built ourselves

00:11:06.979 --> 00:11:14.460
Ourselves with our data and our use cases where we showed our code and converted it throughout the course

00:11:15.179 --> 00:11:17.179
Later, they were comfortable

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:23.380
With learning taking courses off the shelf and learning by themselves on their own

00:11:24.260 --> 00:11:30.099
Those who were scared to start we organized code alone and get together events

00:11:30.659 --> 00:11:35.020
Where in small groups people were sitting next to each other

00:11:35.659 --> 00:11:39.179
Actually in the same class with the support of mentor

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:47.099
They were doing a project together a small little project but together that helped a lot

00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:53.419
We also gave people JNAI tools and

00:11:54.979 --> 00:11:57.419
Not to write the code but to learn

00:11:57.739 --> 00:12:04.659
To learn the code that was created by somebody else who left the organization ages ago and forgot to leave any

00:12:05.099 --> 00:12:06.900
documentation whatsoever

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:10.739
we they use these JNAI tools to

00:12:11.539 --> 00:12:18.820
Convert the existing code into pseudocode in plain English code to understand and better and to find efficiencies and

00:12:19.739 --> 00:12:21.380
also to

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:25.260
To learn the new code that was created by somebody else in the team

00:12:25.700 --> 00:12:30.260
One analyst called charge BT a patient mentor a tutor

00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:37.059
Available day and night to answer their questions that were honestly embarrassed to ask their neighbors

00:12:37.219 --> 00:12:41.460
Their the neighbors in the in in the office or their mentor

00:12:43.219 --> 00:12:45.460
Altogether our analyst completed

00:12:46.419 --> 00:12:49.260
40,000 hours of training they were

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:54.419
Scared at the beginning and we were scared to give them that much training

00:12:54.580 --> 00:13:02.219
But at the end they appreciated the the challenge and one analyst said learning was fun

00:13:02.219 --> 00:13:08.260
I appreciated the opportunity it brought excitement to my day-to-day work

00:13:10.659 --> 00:13:14.659
But the real game-changer was structured mentorship

00:13:15.619 --> 00:13:22.820
We hired a brand new team of mentors not based on their sharpest code, but based on their

00:13:23.700 --> 00:13:26.299
ability to teach and ability to create

00:13:27.179 --> 00:13:29.179
psychological safety

00:13:29.979 --> 00:13:37.059
Every team got a mentor and every mentor supported several teams. They were providing technical support

00:13:37.580 --> 00:13:43.179
Answering questions help me sue the code with our in Python code with server questions

00:13:44.140 --> 00:13:47.140
They also helped build confidence in

00:13:47.619 --> 00:13:51.260
Analysts, they were talking to them individually and in group

00:13:51.260 --> 00:13:56.059
They comment them down if it's needed every team went through

00:13:56.739 --> 00:13:59.500
Emotional transformation along the project

00:14:00.020 --> 00:14:05.780
But the way the mentors support they felt safer their words not mine

00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:13.619
To see our project on one slide as one image think of our journey like being out in the open water

00:14:14.260 --> 00:14:20.020
There is a lighthouse the executive support that is steady visible and kept us oriented

00:14:20.020 --> 00:14:26.140
No matter how rough the waters got it cleared the workload and gave us space to learn

00:14:28.099 --> 00:14:32.020
Then it's a small diverse and trusted crew

00:14:32.260 --> 00:14:37.659
Roaring and sink and providing support to everyone and building trust in everyone

00:14:37.820 --> 00:14:42.859
They listen they supported they encouraged they appreciated the effort

00:14:43.580 --> 00:14:44.940
and

00:14:44.940 --> 00:14:46.940
Then the swimmers in the water

00:14:47.619 --> 00:14:49.619
Analysts equipped with training

00:14:49.859 --> 00:14:55.299
Mentors and the safety net to admit that they didn't know something put together

00:14:55.460 --> 00:14:58.340
That's how the transformation became possible

00:14:59.380 --> 00:15:06.900
When we first stepped into the ocean of open source the waves looked big and the current felt strong

00:15:06.900 --> 00:15:10.859
But today we're not just staying afloat. We are swimming

00:15:11.539 --> 00:15:13.539
confidently together

00:15:13.700 --> 00:15:18.539
We made the leap by investing in our own analysts together

00:15:19.780 --> 00:15:25.020
350 people migrated one and a half million lines of code over

00:15:25.380 --> 00:15:27.380
500 products and over

00:15:27.859 --> 00:15:33.619
18,000 data sets today hundred percent of our work is happening in R and Python

00:15:34.020 --> 00:15:38.940
We started sharing our code internally inside our organization

00:15:38.940 --> 00:15:43.219
We are donating pieces of our code in the common code repository

00:15:43.619 --> 00:15:44.780
our

00:15:44.780 --> 00:15:47.020
analysts our old culture

00:15:47.739 --> 00:15:49.859
isolated and cautious now

00:15:50.380 --> 00:15:57.820
Slowly, but surely has been changing to something more collaborative and more experimental and this is only

00:15:58.020 --> 00:16:00.020
the shoreline

00:16:00.099 --> 00:16:02.099
the future

00:16:02.179 --> 00:16:06.140
The ocean hasn't gotten any smaller tech keeps evolving

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:12.099
Open source keeps expanding health data science keeps raising ahead and that's okay

00:16:12.419 --> 00:16:19.380
Because now we are ready for it. We keep learning keep pushing and keep building in the future

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:27.260
We can focus on speeding up our delivery and that will give us time to learn something new and to innovate

00:16:27.780 --> 00:16:33.979
Today, we are not the same organization as before. We didn't just adopt open source

00:16:34.059 --> 00:16:36.059
We adopted openness

00:16:36.500 --> 00:16:38.219
We see ourselves

00:16:38.219 --> 00:16:45.739
Contributing to public open source projects now many of our clients and partners in Canada and abroad have started

00:16:45.859 --> 00:16:51.500
Exploring open source tools same as us. They started coming to us and asking for advice

00:16:52.140 --> 00:16:54.140
for our recipe for success

00:16:54.299 --> 00:17:01.260
So today we are not just swimming ourselves. We are guiding others through their own transformation

00:17:01.659 --> 00:17:05.099
We are making ripples beyond our organization

00:17:05.099 --> 00:17:10.699
I will leave you with this if you're standing at your own cliff wondering whether to jump

00:17:10.900 --> 00:17:17.660
Don't wait for the waters to feel warm. If we could do it slow heavy legacy bound organization

00:17:17.660 --> 00:17:22.660
You can do it too. My advice jump in the water is fine

00:17:23.339 --> 00:17:26.699
Behind this transformation was a team of people who made it happen

00:17:26.699 --> 00:17:34.579
We have more lessons to share so if you want to talk to us, here is how you can reach us. Thank you

